May I suggest to the Department for Work and Pensions that it applies common sense and human compassion when dealing with vulnerable and disabled people (Court rules universal credit treated disabled unlawfully, 30 January). I don’t think it needs a serious case panel to tell it that.James GilgallonLondon • Adrian Chiles is absolutely right about the bonding significance of football chat (G2, 30 January). Years ago, in the days when I had hair, I used to go to a very nice barber whose only topic of conversation was Blackburn Rovers FC. I don’t do football at all, but I found that I had to read the football pages of the newspaper assiduously for a week or so before a planned appointment just so I could keep up.Patrick Hoyte Wootton Courtenay, Somerset • Football bores in the workplace are a genuine problem for colleagues of both sexes. Couldn’t offices have a “football box” equivalent to a swear box? The bores could drone on and at least it would go to a good cause.Derek McMillanDurrington-on-Sea, West Sussex • Readers are upset by Gary Lineker’s BBC salary of £1.75m (Letters, 30 January). Ant and Dec on ITV get £10m a year between them. And they annoy the hell out of me!John RichardsOxford • Re an octogenarian Guardian readers’ marmalade-making club (Letters, 30 January), could it be called the Preservation Order?Michael CunninghamWolverhampton • Join the debate – email guardian.letters@theguardian.com • Read more Guardian letters – click here to visit gu.com/letters • Do you have a photo you’d like to share with Guardian readers? Click here to upload it and we’ll publish the best submissions in the letters spread of our print edition